 realization that power stems from within and that we are just mortals and pawns to the gods, as worthy as a plat is to one of us.  Only worth thinking of when there aren't any.<br>
<br>
Perhaps the gods are nothing more than the tangible representation of Norrath's beliefs...it would explain how the powerful gods can be killed but will wink back into existence as quickly as they winked out - the beliefs of their followers sustain them.  Zebux may be the faltering hope of those who were turned away by their gods, the belief that something greater is out there no matter how depraved things may become. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ukelisk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kelisk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>No, YOU'RE evil<br>Look out! ...Rar!<br>New lizard Mod!</span><br>  Posts: 570<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/19/02 7:58:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2723.topic&index=19>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Hrm</span><hr size=1> I've always thought that the explanation for the Gods' returning after &quot;death&quot; was due to the fact that they DON'T actually exist.  They're just manifestations of certain aspects of the Nameless (the Gods of Power are anyway, the other gods are creations of them).  When you kill a god you're really not killing anything, just an avatar of that small piece of the nameless's being.  Of course, none of my characters would believe that IC. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=lest>Lest</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 167<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/19/02 8:42:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2723.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> dead gods and stuff</span><hr size=1> I like where this is going. <br>
<br>
While I/Lest have never been at a level to witness the death of a god, I've been reading and writing fantasy for a long time and I've alway seen the physical manifestations of gods as a plaything for them, a way of Being Someplace when lesser creatures require it to perceive them. It would probably piss a god off pretty badly to have that physical manifestion destroyed, but he/she/it will always come back whenever he/she/it feels like it. <br>
<br>
I don't plan too intensely when I write Lest stories - they come out better when I give myself a time limit and say &quot;write it or don't&quot; - but something popped out in one story that accidentally summed up my view of (lowercase) gods of fantasy worlds: &quot;But gods are just gods and they all answer to a higher power anyway.&quot; <br>
<br>
MadRain, you've nailed where I've decided to go with Lest on the head - he'll obviously never find that lost city physically, so he'll eventually find it spiritually, reaching a sort of peace with his place in the universe. <br>
<br>
